	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Seychelles: local sector development is threatened by EU food-safety and sanitary regulations</h1>

			
			<h4>
												14 November 2004
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p> President James Michel of the Seychelles held discussions on May 5th 2004 with representatives of both the industrial and artisanal fishery sectors. They mapped out strategies to resolve the problems faced by the industry, and to keep Port Victoria ahead of its regional competitors. A proposal was made to formulate a package specifically for the semi-industrial (sector), where it is felt that the potential exists to improve earnings from species such as tuna.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p> Particular mention was made of the difficulties faced by the industry with swordfish exports to the EU. In mid-2002 the EC issued a health directive on exports of swordfish from the Indian Ocean archipelago due to high levels of the heavy metal cadmium, potentially harmful to human health.</p><p> EU legislation on heavy-metal contamination in food is becoming increasingly strict. The sampling methods and the methods of analysis for the official control of the levels of lead, cadmium, mercury and 3-MCPD in foodstuffs are clearly defined and must be applied to ACP fishery products.</p><p> The EU has initiated a &quot;rapid-alert system for food and fee &quot;dnd publishes weekly &quot;alert notification &quot;snd &quot;information notifications?. Alerts are triggered by the EU member state that detects the problem and which has initiated the relevant measures, such as withdrawal/recall.</p><p> Since the inception of the system, fishery products have figured prominently in the weekly reports. EU actions against fish exports from the Seychelles have had a major impact on local fishermen. The Seychelles earned 18 million rupees ($3.27 million) from artisanal fishing including swordfish in 2002, but revenue fell by over 50% to 8.7 million rupees in 2003 after the EU’s restrictions on exports were imposed.</p><p> The islands' fishing industry, the bulk of which is tuna fishing, is one of the mainstays of the economy, generating 920 million rupees ($167.27 million) in 2002. Fishermen specialising in swordfish have attempted to diversify into tuna fishing, but due to lack of equipment and experience, this has not been successful.</p><p>
 The Seychelles Fishing Authority is hoping to provide training on tuna-catching methods and to lobby the EU to recognise that cadmium from swordfish is no more dangerous than that found in many other food products. On the other hand strong local and international demand for shark fins is encouraging local fishermen to switch to catching sharks, but only for their fins, a highly questionable and wasteful practice, with serious implications for the conservation of resources. <br/> </p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<a href="http://www.seychelles-online.com.sc/archives/2060504.html" target="_self">Press article in Seychelles on Line</a> </p><p>
<a href="http://europa.eu.int/comm/food/fs/inspections/special_topics/guide_thirdcountries_en.pdf" target="_self">EU legislation on heavy-metal contamination in food: procedures for thir...</a> </p><p>

<a href="http://europa.eu.int/comm/food/index_en.htm" target="_self">EU’s rapid alert system for food and feed</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> The banning of shipments of fish containing high levels of heavy metals is a major concern to those ACP countries whose export earnings are particularly dependent on tuna-like species and other fish that accumulate heavy metals. On the one hand, the heavy-metal content of fish cannot be controlled, and on the other there is evidence of uneven application of the regulations across the EU.</p><p> Many species of fish naturally contain significant levels of heavy metals (mercury, cadmium etc) which, if eaten in large amounts, may be harmful to health. Of particular importance in this regard are high-value species like swordfish, and many tuna like species that are major export products from several ACP countries (e.g. the Seychelles and the Solomon Islands).</p><p> The way that random testing for heavy metals in fish entering the EU market is currently carried out may mean that some importing countries are more discriminated against than others. There are reports that some countries (like the UK) have a higher level of inspection than other EU member states. This would particularly affect the Solomon Islands and the Seychelles as the UK is their main market for canned tuna. The way inspections are carried out could also mean that tuna caught by EU vessels fishing under other fishing agreements (such as those of France and Spain) may be receiving more favourable treatment, entering the EU market without being tested as rigorously as ACP imports.</p><p> While there is an EU regulation ((EC) No 466/2001) that sets maximum limits for heavy metals in a number of listed species of fish and shell fish, those listed do not include such species as swordfish. The maximum levels set for swordfish have been set at twice the maximum levels for other species listed in the regulation in a seemingly arbitrary fashion.</p><p> There is therefore an urgent need:</p>
<ul>

<li>for the harmonisation and standardisation of the food-safety regulations that apply to heavy metals in fish; </li>

<li>to publish some objectively written awareness-raising materials for consumers and traders that highlight the issue of heavy metals in fish. This would also need to take into account consumption levels and the risks to particularly vulnerable groups.</li>

</ul>
<p> In the meantime, heavy-metal contamination in fish is likely to remain a &quot;wild car &quot;dn the pack of non-tariff barriers for restricting access for ACP fishery products to the EU market.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

